<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38222a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38222a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38222a"> 222(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Si murgh / 30 birds</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">At last, standing upon the mysterious island of the Simurgh, and &ldquo;casting a clandestine glance at him they saw thirty birds in him; and when they turned their eyes to themselves, <mark>the thirty birds seemed one Simurgh</mark>: they saw in themselves the entire Simurgh; they saw in the Simurgh the thirty birds entirely.&rdquo; Therefore they arrived at the solution of the problem &ldquo;<i>We</i> and <i>Thou</i>;&rdquo; that is, the identity of God and man. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 130</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The way Joyce wrote down the note is explained by Burton&apos;s footnote on the same page <u>Si</u>= <u>thirty</u> and <u>Murgh</u> = <u>bird</u>. <cite>FW</cite> 358.28 derives from <a name="n56123b" href="n56all.htm#n56123b">N56 (VI.B.41):123(b)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
